The paper discusses data mining techniques and supervised learning to predict the long-term impact of scientific work, which suggests a focus on information retrieval (cs.IR) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also mentions scholarly feature design, which could fall under social and information networks (cs.SI) or digital libraries (cs.DL). Finally, the paper discusses the domain-heterogeneity and dynamics of scientific impact, which could relate to cybernetics (cs.CY).
